			<div class="content" id="post-content-4334211">
									

<blockquote>
<p>This conceptual expansion is large enough that I'd feel the need to refer back to this page every time I saw the format just to be sure that I'm understanding it right in each context.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I considered this but, ultimately, I think that the actual definitions are relatively clear that it shouldn't be particularly difficult to pick up on. Both of the two new Classification Systems work on a 1-5 system and clearly display those numbers and their associated colors as well as the in-universe names. This should, at least, give people an idea of the degree of severity for each classification at a glance.</p>
<p>Additionally, I think the names &quot;Disruption Class&quot; and &quot;Risk Class&quot; do a fairly good job of describing, at the basest level, what those two Classification Scales are referring to.</p>
<p>Hopefully, in time, this can possibly get used more often and people get more used to it, much like what originally happened with Object Classes. We'll see, though.</p>
<p>The intent was always to create this so authors could add it to give some narrative interest to an article if they so desired.</p>

