<p>I read your response (as well as those below it). I admit I may have been a little harsh.</p>
<p>I agree that Thaumiel acts more as a descriptor than a normal object class. Using <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aismallard" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4598089); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=4598089&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1566245705" alt="aismallard" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=4598089)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aismallard" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4598089); return false;">aismallard</a></span>’s comment as a reference, if 3000 didn’t produce Y-909, it would definitely be Keter. I guess my criticism came from the fact that making it a secondary class felt mean-spirited for some reason.</p>
<p>One other issue I have is that the new format feels very static. A number of SCPs have objects classes that had been changed over time. (The whole <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">Safe</span> Euclid thing for example.) The way this format is made makes it hard to show that, in my opinion.</p>

